{
  "doc_id": "50878",
  "text": "IL-10 was discovered as a cytokine synthesis inhibiting factor, and its principal function is the activity inhibition of Th1 cells [CITATION_1] . IL-10 has multiple biological functions on different cell types. In macrophages, IL-10 inhibits ligand-induced activation and the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines from macrophages [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . IL-10 inhibits the proliferation as well as cytokine synthesis of CD4 + T-cells [CITATION_4] . Other immunosuppressive effects have also been reported on eosinophils [CITATION_5] , neutrophils [CITATION_6] , and dendritic cells [CITATION_7] . In contrast to these immunosuppressive effects, IL-10 has been shown to have the abilities of immunostimulation on cytotoxic T-cells [CITATION_8] , and is a growth costimulator for thymocytes and mast cells [CITATION_9] . In this study, AC-2 also inhibited LPS-induced IL-10 gene expression.",
